text=(:if [ authgroup @tas || authgroup @admins || equal {$Author} '' ]:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=edit|Edit this page]] \\%0aStatus: {GradebookArticles.{$Name}$:Status} %0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!{$:Category}]]%0a%0a!Fingerspelling%0a%0a:Author: wtsin%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aA brief look at signs for individual letters or characters%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aFingerspelling is a way of signing individual letters or characters: for instance, letters from the English alphabet. It has existed in some form for over a millennium, and until the 18th century, was seen as the 'educated' way of signing. It became less common as people accepted that using signs for entire words would be more faster and easier.%0a%0aToday, fingerspelling is primarily used in English for proper nouns, uncommon words, or to give emphasis to a specific word. Additionally, it is thought that fingerspelling can improve literacy at a young age by building strong connections with the English alphabet, and can work as a link between ASL and English.%0a%0aFingerspelling's influence can also be seen in words borrowed from other sign languages. When signing a word from a different language for the first time, one would probably sign out its spelling. This method sometimes sticks—for example, the ASL sign for "bus" is simply the signs for "B" "U" and "S" made quickly. This also holds in different languages: for instance, the Japanese Sign Language sign for "computer" is based on the English pronunciation for the word, modified to fit with Japanese characters.%0a%0aSources%0a- https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-22294204%0a- https://asl.land/deaf/fschart.php%0a- https://muse.jhu.edu/article/741061%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 221210-005321-955750#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Signs that Involve Fingerspelling %0a-> - jackagui%0a-> [-09.12.2022 - 16:53-]%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a{[foxdelrange button 221210-005321-955750 {$FullName} ]}%0a(:if1end:)%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aMany signs for colors in ASL involve making the letter that starts the word and shaking it back and forth, including the signs for yellow, green, blue, and purple. The signs for brown and pink also include the hand shape of b and p, respectively. %0a%0aAs well, the sign for "I love you" is derived from the signs for i, l, and y. The sign for i is a hand with your pinky out, the sign for l is a hand with your thumb and pointer out, and the sign for y is a hand with your thumb and pinky out, and the sign for I love you is a hand with your thumb, pointer, and pinky out.%0a%0asource: https://theglobalmontessorinetwork.org/resource/primary/american-sign-language-colors-review/%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 221210-005321-955750#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%0aYou must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a%0a----%0a(:if equal {$Author} {$:Author}:)%0a!!Change article category%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#changearticlecategory:)%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a%0a(:Section: C:)%0a(:Category: SignLanguage:)%0a(:Title: Fingerspelling:)
